@GuyGood few questions -

from the screenshot alone, the smoothing does seems to give better appearance, and could be a feature well desired, but how well does it apply to other different kind of geometries? does the angle need to be selected intelligently, or is that an angle (like 20 degrees perhaps) that work well in general? also, do you have any links to reference on the approach you or others have implemented here?

lastly, if `computeVertexNormals` is replaced with your function, how much penalty in performance (since I guess this probably does more calculations..)

@WestLangley Thanks a ton for your quick reply. I found similar answers by you on Stackoverflow earlier, but I couldn't really believe it. It sounds cumbersome and smelly, as a workaround-more than solid design-to have to duplicate hard edges.

From your older answers I understood that it should be enough to duplicate the hard edges. From your current answer, I understand that we need not only duplicate the edges, but also specify vertex normals. This would imply that simply calling `computeVertexNormals()` would not be sufficient, correct?

Since in my project, I am loading legacy geometry from VRML files, I would have to compute the duplications and the normals, which should be possible once I fully understand the principles.

@WestLangley When I look at a standard ThreeJs Cylinder, rendered with computeVertexNormals(), it gets smooth sides, but the angle between the sides and top and bottom appears to be smooth too.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1441397/22476408/9b2e0a74-e7e2-11e6-88c6-1fcea20355b2.png)

Also, the green cube is an IndexedFaceSet with duplicated edges where sharp. It is triangulated and it shows with the lighting. How can this be avoided? The diagonal edge is not duplicated, so it should appear as smooth I think.

@bartmcleod Yes, in fact I have re-used your function (exported as ES6 module – Note: if anyone wants to reuse it, remove all "scope.log" references, or substitute them with "console.log", since it gets what ever scope the function is, and it might not have a log function), on a complex BufferGeometry I import from an obj file, and works perfectly.
I merge vertices before calling your function, and compute vertex normals after.
Thank you again!
